"This tutorial, part of IN 1400 - Fundamentals of Databases and Database Design and IN 1401 - Fundamentals of Databases by Akila Warnapura, aims for learners to understand advanced data retrieval using Data Query Language (DQL). Structured Query Language (SQL) commands are categorized into DDL (Data Definition Language), DCL (Data Control Language), DML (Data Manipulation Language), and DQL (Data Query Language). SQL Joins are an advanced data retrieval method with several types, including Inner Join, Outer Join (Left, Right, and Full), Natural Join, and Cross Join. An Inner Join connects tables by matching specified columns, while a Left Outer Join matches specified columns with all tuples from the left-hand table, a Right Outer Join does so with all tuples from the right-hand table, and a Full Outer Join matches with all tuples from both sides. A Natural Join automatically connects tables by matching columns with similar names, and a Cross Join matches each tuple in one table to all tuples in another table without any conditions to form a new table. Aggregate functions in SQL return a single value after performing a calculation on multiple values, with common examples being SUM(), MIN(), MAX(), AVG(), and COUNT(). Nested queries, also known as subqueries or inner queries, are SQL queries contained within another SQL query, typically found in the WHERE clause, where their returned data acts as a condition for the main query to refine data retrieval. A correlated nested query, or correlated subquery, reads every row in a table and compares values against related data, returning a unique result set for each candidate row examined by the main query."